comments:
Posted this to news group, and was asked to log this. Basically, if an error is
thrown inside a synchronized section, the debugger says the error is on the line
that has the synchronized modifer. Try running the following code:

public class DebugTest {

  private static int[] testArray = new int[10];
  private static int someVal = 0;
  private static Object lockObject = new Object();

  public static void main(String[] args) {

  synchronized (lockObject) {
    someVal = testArray[-1];	
  }

  }

}

Obviously, an ArrayIndexOutOfBounds exception is thrown, but the debugger says
the error is on line 9, but it's clearly on line 10. Darin Swanson (who replied
to my post asking for this bug report) said that the bebugger just reports what
JVM tells it, but as I'm sure you can see, it is misleading and awkward when the
error is actually being thrown by a method as you can't look into the method to
see it's local variables. I hope something can be done...
